name: Orion
stars: 7 main stars, plus dozens of fainter stars
mythology: A hunter placed in the sky after angering the gods.
formation: Stars born in nearby molecular clouds
age: Several million years for its stars
funFact: Orion’s sword contains a stellar nursery where thousands of new stars are forming!

name: Ursa Major
stars: 7 main stars forming the Big Dipper pattern
mythology: A great bear chased by a hunter across the sky.
bestViewingSeason: Visible all year in the Northern Hemisphere
notableFeatures: The Big Dipper helps locate Polaris
formation: Part of the Milky Way’s stellar neighborhood
funFact: The Big Dipper is just a part of the larger Ursa Major constellation!

name: Scorpius
stars: 18 main stars, many deep-sky objects
mythology: The scorpion sent to defeat the hunter Orion.
formation: Star systems formed from molecular clouds
funFact: Antares is sometimes called the ‘Rival of Mars’ because of its red color!

name: Cassiopeia
stars: 5 main stars, with several faint stars and clusters
mythology: A vain queen placed in the sky as punishment for boasting about her beauty.
bestViewingSeason: Autumn and winter in the Northern Hemisphere
formation: Stars formed in the Perseus arm of the Milky Way
discoveredBy: Known to Greek and other ancient astronomers
funFact: Cassiopeia’s distinctive ‘W’ shape makes it one of the easiest constellations to spot!

name: Lyra
stars: 6 main stars, plus numerous fainter stars
mythology: Represents the lyre of Orpheus, a musical instrument given by the gods.
notableFeatures: Contains Vega – one of the brightest stars
Home to the famous Ring Nebula
formation: Stars formed in the Milky Way’s spiral arm
discoveredBy: Known to ancient civilizations including Greeks and Egyptians
funFact: Vega has been used as a calibration star for astronomical measurements!

name: Perseus
stars: 13 main stars and many fainter stars
mythology: Named after Perseus, the Greek hero who rescued Andromeda from a sea monster.
notableFeatures: Algol is a famous eclipsing binary star
observations: Used by ancient astronomers for navigation
formation: Stars formed from nearby interstellar clouds
funFact: Algol’s brightness regularly dips because one star passes in front of the other!

name: Taurus
stars: 19 main stars plus many clusters
mythology: Represents a bull associated with Zeus and ancient fertility myths.
notableFeatures: Home to the famous Pleiades star cluster
formation: Formed from nearby stellar nurseries
funFact: The Pleiades cluster has been important in mythology and agriculture for thousands of years!

name: Andromeda
stars: 32 known stars and surrounding systems
mythology: Represents the chained princess rescued by Perseus from a sea monster.
notableFeatures: Hosts the nearest major galaxy to the Milky Way
Key in studies of galactic evolution
observations: Target of amateur and professional astronomers
formation: Galactic structure evolved over billions of years
funFact: The Andromeda Galaxy will collide with the Milky Way in about 4.5 billion years!

name: Hercules
stars: 14 main stars plus numerous fainter stars and deep-sky objects
mythology: Named after Hercules, the Greek hero known for his strength and labors.
notableFeatures: Messier 13 is one of the most spectacular globular clusters
formation: Stars grouped by gravity in clusters and systems
funFact: Messier 13 contains hundreds of thousands of stars packed tightly together!

name: Pegasus
stars: 9 main stars and many faint stars
mythology: Represents the winged horse Pegasus, born from the blood of Medusa.
notableFeatures: Contains the Great Square of Pegasus
Rich in star clusters and galaxies
observations: Used by ancient travelers for orientation
formation: Stars formed in the outer regions of the Milky Way
age: Hundreds of millions to billions of years
discoveredBy: Known to Greek and other ancient cultures
funFact: The Great Square of Pegasus is a useful guidepost in stargazing!

name: Aquarius
stars: 11 main stars with several deep-sky objects
mythology: Represents the water-bearer pouring life-giving water.
bestViewingSeason: Autumn and winter in the Northern Hemisphere
formation: Formed from stars in the outer Milky Way regions
funFact: Aquarius is often associated with rainfall and fertility in many mythologies!

name: Capricornus
stars: 8 main stars with several nearby objects
mythology: Represents the sea-goat, a creature with the front half of a goat and tail of a fish.
formation: Stars formed in the Milky Way's outer regions
funFact: Capricornus is one of the oldest recognized constellations and linked with ancient sea myths!

name: Pisces
stars: 18 main stars with some fainter ones nearby
mythology: Represents two fish tied together, symbolizing love and unity.
formation: Stars formed from interstellar clouds within the Milky Way
discoveredBy: Known to ancient Greeks and Babylonians
funFact: Pisces is one of the constellations used to mark the location of the vernal equinox in ancient times!

name: Aries
stars: 15 main stars with some faint clusters nearby
mythology: Represents the ram whose fleece became the Golden Fleece sought by Jason and the Argonauts.
notableFeatures: Associated with ancient myths of quest and adventure
formation: Stars formed in local stellar regions within the Milky Way
funFact: Aries is one of the oldest recognized constellations and connected to stories of heroism and exploration!

name: Cancer
stars: 5 main stars and several star clusters
mythology: Represents the crab sent by Hera to distract Hercules during his labors.
notableFeatures: Home to the Beehive star cluster
observations: Popular for amateur astronomers to spot clusters
formation: Stars formed from interstellar clouds within the Milky Way
discoveredBy: Known since ancient civilizations like Babylonian and Greek
funFact: The Beehive Cluster in Cancer is one of the nearest open clusters to Earth!

name: Leo
stars: 9 main stars and several clusters
mythology: Represents the lion slain by Hercules as one of his labors.
notableFeatures: Contains the famous Leo Triplet of galaxies
observations: Used by astronomers for galaxy observations
formation: Stars formed from interstellar material within the Milky Way
discoveredBy: Known since ancient civilizations like Greeks and Babylonians
funFact: Regulus is a multiple star system located at the heart of Leo!

name: Virgo
stars: 15 main stars and many galaxies
mythology: Represents a maiden associated with harvest and agriculture.
formation: Galaxies and stars formed over billions of years
funFact: The Virgo Cluster is one of the largest galaxy clusters in the nearby universe!

name: Libra
stars: 6 main stars with some fainter ones
mythology: Represents the scales of balance and justice.
formation: Stars formed from interstellar clouds within the Milky Way
funFact: Libra is the only zodiac constellation representing an inanimate object!

name: Scutum
stars: 5 main stars with several clusters nearby
mythology: Named after the shield of John III Sobieski, a Polish king.
notableFeatures: Contains one of the richest star clusters, M11
Located along the Milky Way’s band
formation: Stars formed in dense regions of the Milky Way
funFact: Messier 11, in Scutum, is one of the richest open clusters visible with binoculars!

name: Sagittarius
stars: 12 main stars with many clusters and nebulae
mythology: Represents the archer aiming towards the center of the Milky Way.
observations: Important for studying the center of our galaxy
formation: Stars and nebulae formed from dense molecular clouds
age: Millions of years to billions for its objects
funFact: Sagittarius contains Sagittarius A*, the supermassive black hole at the Milky Way’s core!

name: Ophiuchus
stars: 11 main stars and several clusters
mythology: Represents a man holding a serpent, associated with healing.
formation: Stars formed from interstellar clouds within the Milky Way
funFact: Ophiuchus is sometimes called the '13th zodiac', but it’s not officially part of the zodiac belt!

name: Cygnus
stars: 16 main stars and many fainter stars
mythology: Represents a swan, associated with several Greek myths.
notableFeatures: Rich in nebulae and star-forming regions
formation: Stars formed in dense regions of the Milky Way
age: Several million to hundreds of millions of years
funFact: Deneb, in Cygnus, is one of the most luminous stars known!

name: Aquila
stars: 9 main stars and several faint stars
mythology: Represents the eagle that carried Zeus’ thunderbolts.
notableFeatures: Contains Altair, part of the Summer Triangle
formation: Stars formed from nearby interstellar clouds
funFact: Altair rotates extremely fast, completing a rotation in less than a day!

name: Gemini
stars: 14 main stars and several faint ones
mythology: Represents the twins Castor and Pollux from Greek mythology.
formation: Stars formed from local molecular clouds
funFact: Pollux is an orange giant, while Castor is a multiple star system!

name: Canis Major
stars: 8 main stars with several bright ones
mythology: Represents the greater dog following Orion, the hunter.
notableFeatures: Home to Sirius, the brightest star in the night sky
formation: Stars formed from interstellar clouds in the Milky Way
age: Millions to hundreds of millions of years
funFact: Sirius is actually a binary star system, consisting of Sirius A and a faint white dwarf Sirius B!

name: Canis Minor
stars: 2 main stars with a few faint ones
mythology: Represents the lesser dog accompanying Orion, the hunter.
notableFeatures: Home to Procyon, the 8th brightest star in the night sky
observations: Easy to spot due to Procyon
formation: Stars formed from local molecular clouds within the Milky Way
funFact: Procyon is part of the Winter Triangle along with Sirius and Betelgeuse!

name: Auriga
stars: 6 main stars with several clusters
mythology: Represents the charioteer in Greek mythology.
notableFeatures: Contains Capella, a bright yellow giant
formation: Stars formed from nearby interstellar clouds
funFact: Capella is actually a multiple star system of two binary pairs!

name: Cepheus
stars: 9 main stars with some fainter ones
mythology: Represents King Cepheus, husband of Cassiopeia and father of Andromeda.
notableFeatures: Part of the royal family trio with Cassiopeia and Andromeda
observations: Good for star and cluster observations
formation: Stars formed from molecular clouds in the Milky Way
funFact: Alderamin is a white main-sequence star and the brightest in Cepheus!

name: Draco
stars: 14 main stars and several fainter stars
mythology: Represents the dragon guarding the golden apples in Greek mythology.
notableFeatures: Long, winding shape around the North Pole
formation: Stars formed in the Milky Way’s outer regions
funFact: Draco snakes around the Little Dipper and contains some of the oldest stars in the Milky Way!

name: Ursa Minor
stars: 7 main stars forming the Little Dipper asterism
mythology: Represents the Little Bear from Greek mythology.
notableFeatures: Little Dipper asterism used for navigation
formation: Stars formed from molecular clouds
funFact: Polaris, in Ursa Minor, is nearly aligned with the North Celestial Pole!

name: Bootes
stars: 7 main stars with several fainter stars
mythology: Represents the herdsman or plowman in Greek mythology.
notableFeatures: Home to Arcturus, a bright orange giant
observations: Good for observing bright stars and clusters
formation: Stars formed from interstellar clouds
funFact: Arcturus is one of the brightest stars in the night sky and part of the Spring Triangle!

name: Sagitta
stars: 4 main stars
mythology: Represents the arrow of Hercules or Cupid.
observations: Easy to spot due to its arrow shape
formation: Stars formed from local interstellar material
funFact: Sagitta is one of the smallest constellations but easy to recognize because of its arrow shape!
